<p></p>
<p>Let's find \(\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx}\) for \({@expr@}\)</p>
<p>The first step is to differentiate both sides with respect to \(x\).</p>
<p>Remember that the key to this is to always think of \(y\) as a function of \(x\), or \(y=y(x)\)</p>

<p>\(
\begin{align}
\displaystyle \frac{d}{dx} ({@aa*y^bb+cc*x^dd@}) & = & \displaystyle \frac{d}{dx} ({@ee*x^gg, simp@}) \\
\displaystyle \frac{d}{dy} ({@aa*y^bb@}) \cdot \displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx} + \displaystyle \frac{d}{dx} ({@cc*x^dd@}) & = & \displaystyle \frac{d}{dx} ({@ee*x^gg, simp@})\\
\displaystyle {@diff(aa*y^bb,y)@} \cdot \displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx} + {@diff(cc*x^dd,x)@} & = & \displaystyle {@diff(ee*x^gg,x)@} \\
\displaystyle {@diff(aa*y^bb,y)@} \cdot \displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx}  & = & \displaystyle {@diff(ee*x^gg-cc*x^dd,x)@} \\
\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx}  & = & \displaystyle {@ta_2@}\\
\end{align}
\)</p>]]></text>
